abstract = {The most rapid loss of ice from the Antarctic Ice Sheet is observed$\backslash$nwhere ice streams flow into the ocean and begin to float, forming the$\backslash$ngreat Antarctic ice shelves that surround much of the continent. Because$\backslash$nthese ice shelves are floating, their thinning does not greatly$\backslash$ninfluence sea level. However, they also buttress the ice streams$\backslash$ndraining the ice sheet, and so ice shelf changes do significantly$\backslash$ninfluence sea level by altering the discharge of grounded ice.$\backslash$nCurrently, the most significant loss of mass from the ice shelves is$\backslash$nfrom melting at the base (although iceberg calving is a close second).$\backslash$nAccessing the ocean beneath ice shelves is extremely difficult, so$\backslash$nnumerical models are invaluable for understanding the processes$\backslash$ngoverning basal melting. This paper describes the different ways in$\backslash$nwhich ice shelf/ocean interactions are modeled and discusses emerging$\backslash$ndirections that will enhance understanding of how the ice shelves are$\backslash$nmelting now and how this might change in the future.},
